04892  *
04893  * This register contains assorted control bits.
04894  *
04895  */
04896 union cvmx_sriomaintx_port_0_ctl {
04897     uint32_t u32;
04898     struct cvmx_sriomaintx_port_0_ctl_s {
04899 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04900     uint32_t pt_width                     : 2;  /**< Hardware port width:
04901                                                          0x0 = One Lane supported.
04902                                                          0x1 = One/Four Lanes supported.
04903                                                          0x2 = One/Two Lanes supported.
04904                                                          0x3 = One/Two/Four Lanes supported.
04905                                                          This value is a copy of SRIO()_IP_FEATURE[PT_WIDTH]
04906                                                          limited by the number of lanes the MAC has. */
04907     uint32_t it_width                     : 3;  /**< Initialized port width:
04908                                                          0x0 = Single-lane, lane 0.
04909                                                          0x1 = Single-lane, lane 1 or 2.
04910                                                          0x2 = Four-lane.
04911                                                          0x3 = Two-lane.
04912                                                          0x7 = Link uninitialized.
04913                                                          Others = Reserved. */
04914     uint32_t ov_width                     : 3;  /**< Override Port Width.  Writing this register causes
04915                                                          the port to reinitialize.
04916                                                          0x0 = No override all lanes possible.
04917                                                          0x1 = Reserved.
04918                                                          0x2 = Force single-lane, lane 0.
04919                                                          If Ln 0 is unavailable try lane 2 then lane 1.
04920                                                          0x3 = Force single-lane, lane 2.
04921                                                          If Ln 2 is unavailable try lane 1 then lane 0.
04922                                                          0x4 = Reserved.
04923                                                          0x5 = Enable two-lane, disable four-lane.
04924                                                          0x6 = Enable four-lane, disable two-lane.
04925                                                          0x7 = All lanes sizes enabled. */
04926     uint32_t reserved_23_23               : 1;
04927     uint32_t o_enable                     : 1;  /**< Port output enable. When cleared, port will generate control symbols and respond
04928                                                          to maintenance transactions only. When set, all transactions are allowed. */
04929     uint32_t i_enable                     : 1;  /**< Port input enable. When cleared, port will generate control symbols and respond
04930                                                          to maintenance packets only. All other packets will not be accepted. */
04931     uint32_t dis_err                      : 1;  /**< Disable error checking.  For diagnostic use only. */
04932     uint32_t mcast                        : 1;  /**< Reserved. */
04933     uint32_t reserved_18_18               : 1;
04934     uint32_t enumb                        : 1;  /**< Enumeration boundry. Software can use this bit to determine port enumeration. */
04935     uint32_t reserved_16_16               : 1;
04936     uint32_t ex_width                     : 2;  /**< Extended port width not supported. */
04937     uint32_t ex_stat                      : 2;  /**< Extended port width status. 0x0 = not supported. */
04938     uint32_t suppress                     : 8;  /**< Retransmit suppression mask.  CRF not Supported. */
04939     uint32_t stp_port                     : 1;  /**< Stop on failed port. This bit is used with the DROP_PKT bit to force certain
04940                                                          behavior when the error rate failed threshold has been met or exceeded. */
04941     uint32_t drop_pkt                     : 1;  /**< Drop on failed port. This bit is used with the STP_PORT bit to force certain
04942                                                          behavior when the error rate failed threshold has been met or exceeded. */
04943     uint32_t prt_lock                     : 1;  /**< When this bit is cleared, the packets that may be
04944                                                          received and issued are controlled by the state of
04945                                                          the O_ENABLE and I_ENABLE bits.  When this bit is
04946                                                          set, this port is stopped and is not enabled to
04947                                                          receive any packets; the input port can still
04948                                                          follow the training procedure and can still send
04949                                                          respond to link-requests; all received packets
04950                                                          return packet-not-accepted control symbols to
04951                                                          force an error condition to be signaled by the
04952                                                          sending device.  The O_ENABLE bit should also be
04953                                                          cleared to disable packet output. */
04954     uint32_t pt_type                      : 1;  /**< Port type.  1 = Serial port. */
04955 #else
04956     uint32_t pt_type                      : 1;
04957     uint32_t prt_lock                     : 1;
04958     uint32_t drop_pkt                     : 1;
04959     uint32_t stp_port                     : 1;
04960     uint32_t suppress                     : 8;
04961     uint32_t ex_stat                      : 2;
04962     uint32_t ex_width                     : 2;

04964     uint32_t enumb                        : 1;

04966     uint32_t mcast                        : 1;

04968     uint32_t i_enable                     : 1;

05150 /**
05151  * cvmx_sriomaint#_port_0_ctl2
05152  *
05153  * These registers are accessed when a local processor or an external
05154  * device wishes to examine the port baudrate information.  The automatic
05155  * baud rate feature is not available on this device. The SUP_* and ENB_*
05156  * fields are set directly by the SRIO()_STATUS_REG[SPD] bits as a
05157  * reference but otherwise have no effect.
05158  *
05159  * WARNING!!  Writes to this register will reinitialize the SRIO link.
05160  */

05170                                                          0x3 = 3.125 GBaud.

05173                                                          0x6-0xF = Reserved. */

05176     uint32_t sup_125g                     : 1;  /**< 1.25 GB rate operation supported.
05177                                                          Set when the interface SerDes lanes are operating
05178                                                          at 1.25 Gbaud (as selected by SRIO()_STATUS_REG[SPD]). */
05179     uint32_t enb_125g                     : 1;  /**< 1.25 GB rate operation enable.
05180                                                          Set when the interface SerDes lanes are operating
05181                                                          at 1.25 Gbaud (as selected by SRIO()_STATUS_REG[SPD]). */
05182     uint32_t sup_250g                     : 1;  /**< 2.50 GB rate operation supported.
05183                                                          Set when the interface SerDes lanes are operating
05184                                                          at 2.5 Gbaud (as selected by SRIO()_STATUS_REG[SPD]). */
05185     uint32_t enb_250g                     : 1;  /**< 2.50 GB rate operation enable.
05186                                                          Set when the interface SerDes lanes are operating
05187                                                          at 2.5 Gbaud (as selected by SRIO()_STATUS_REG[SPD]). */
05188     uint32_t sup_312g                     : 1;  /**< 3.125 GB rate operation supported.

05201     uint32_t enb_625g                     : 1;  /**< 6.25 GB rate operation enable. */

05235 /**
05236  * cvmx_sriomaint#_port_0_err_stat
05237  *
05238  * This register displays port error and status information.  Several port error conditions are
05239  * captured here and must be cleared by writing 1's to the individual bits.
05240  */
05241 union cvmx_sriomaintx_port_0_err_stat {
05242     uint32_t u32;
05243     struct cvmx_sriomaintx_port_0_err_stat_s {
05244 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
05245     uint32_t reserved_27_31               : 5;
05246     uint32_t pkt_drop                     : 1;  /**< Output packet dropped. */
05247     uint32_t o_fail                       : 1;  /**< Output port has encountered a failure condition,
05248                                                          meaning the port's failed error threshold has
05249                                                          reached SRIOMAINT()_ERB_ERR_RATE_THR[ER_FAIL] value. */
05250     uint32_t o_dgrad                      : 1;  /**< Output port has encountered a degraded condition,
05251                                                          meaning the port's degraded threshold has
05252                                                          reached SRIOMAINT()_ERB_ERR_RATE_THR[ER_DGRAD]
05253                                                          value. */
05254     uint32_t reserved_21_23               : 3;
05255     uint32_t o_retry                      : 1;  /**< Output retry encountered.  This bit is set when
05256                                                          bit 18 is set. */
05257     uint32_t o_rtried                     : 1;  /**< Output port has received a packet-retry condition
05258                                                          and cannot make forward progress.  This bit is set
05259                                                          when  bit 18 is set and is cleared when a packet-
05260                                                          accepted or a packet-not-accepted control symbol
05261                                                          is received. */
05262     uint32_t o_sm_ret                     : 1;  /**< Output port state machine has received a
05263                                                          packet-retry control symbol and is retrying the
05264                                                          packet. */
05265     uint32_t o_error                      : 1;  /**< Output error encountered and possibly recovered
05266                                                          from.  This sticky bit is set with bit 16. */
05267     uint32_t o_sm_err                     : 1;  /**< Output port state machine has encountered an
05268                                                          error. */
05269     uint32_t reserved_11_15               : 5;
05270     uint32_t i_sm_ret                     : 1;  /**< Input port state machine has received a
05271                                                          packet-retry control symbol and is retrying the
05272                                                          packet. */
05273     uint32_t i_error                      : 1;  /**< Input error encountered and possibly recovered
05274                                                          from.  This sticky bit is set with bit 8. */
05275     uint32_t i_sm_err                     : 1;  /**< Input port state machine has encountered an
05276                                                          error. */
05277     uint32_t reserved_5_7                 : 3;
05278     uint32_t pt_write                     : 1;  /**< Port has encountered a condition which required it
05279                                                          initiate a maintenance port-write operation.
05280                                                          Never set by hardware. */
05281     uint32_t reserved_3_3                 : 1;
05282     uint32_t pt_error                     : 1;  /**< Input or output port has encountered an
05283                                                          unrecoverable error condition. */
05284     uint32_t pt_ok                        : 1;  /**< Input or output port are intitialized and the port
05285                                                          is exchanging error free control symbols with
05286                                                          attached device. */
05287     uint32_t pt_uinit                     : 1;  /**< Port is uninitialized.  This bit and bit 1 are
05288                                                          mutually exclusive. */
05289 #else
05290     uint32_t pt_uinit                     : 1;
05291     uint32_t pt_ok                        : 1;
05292     uint32_t pt_error                     : 1;
05293     uint32_t reserved_3_3                 : 1;
05294     uint32_t pt_write                     : 1;
05295     uint32_t reserved_5_7                 : 3;
05296     uint32_t i_sm_err                     : 1;
05297     uint32_t i_error                      : 1;
05298     uint32_t i_sm_ret                     : 1;
05299     uint32_t reserved_11_15               : 5;
05300     uint32_t o_sm_err                     : 1;
05301     uint32_t o_error                      : 1;
05302     uint32_t o_sm_ret                     : 1;
05303     uint32_t o_rtried                     : 1;
05304     uint32_t o_retry                      : 1;
05305     uint32_t reserved_21_23               : 3;
05306     uint32_t o_dgrad                      : 1;
05307     uint32_t o_fail                       : 1;
05308     uint32_t pkt_drop                     : 1;
05309     uint32_t reserved_27_31               : 5;
05310 #endif
05311     } s;
05312     struct cvmx_sriomaintx_port_0_err_stat_s cn63xx;
05313     struct cvmx_sriomaintx_port_0_err_stat_s cn63xxp1;

05319 /**
05320  * cvmx_sriomaint#_port_0_link_req
05321  *
05322  * Writing this register generates the link request symbol or eight device reset
05323  * symbols. The progress of the request can be determined by reading
05324  * SRIOMAINT()_PORT_0_LINK_RESP. Only a single request should be generated at a time.
05325  */
05326 union cvmx_sriomaintx_port_0_link_req {
05327     uint32_t u32;
05328     struct cvmx_sriomaintx_port_0_link_req_s {

05331     uint32_t cmd                          : 3;  /**< Link request command.
05332                                                          0x3 = Reset device.
05333                                                          0x4 = Link request.
05334                                                          _ All other values reserved. */
05335 #else
05336     uint32_t cmd                          : 3;
05337     uint32_t reserved_3_31                : 29;
05338 #endif

05449 /**
05450  * cvmx_sriomaint#_port_lt_ctl
05451  *
05452  * This register controls the timeout for link layer transactions.  It is used as the timeout
05453  * between sending a packet (of any type) or link request to receiving the corresponding link
05454  * acknowledge or link-response.  Each count represents 200 ns.  The minimum timeout period is
05455  * the TIMEOUT x200 ns and the maximum is twice that number.  A value less than 32 may not
05456  * guarantee that all timeout errors will be reported correctly.  When the timeout period expires
05457  * the packet or link request is dropped and the error is logged in the LNK_TOUT field of the
05458  * SRIOMAINT()_ERB_ERR_DET register. A value of 0 in this register will allow the packet or
05459  * link request to be issued but it will timeout immediately.  This value is not recommended for
05460  * normal operation.
05461  */

05463     uint32_t u32;
05464     struct cvmx_sriomaintx_port_lt_ctl_s {
05465 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
05466     uint32_t timeout                      : 24; /**< Timeout value. */
05467     uint32_t reserved_0_7                 : 8;
05468 #else
05469     uint32_t reserved_0_7                 : 8;
05470     uint32_t timeout                      : 24;
05471 #endif
05472     } s;
05473     struct cvmx_sriomaintx_port_lt_ctl_s  cn63xx;
05474     struct cvmx_sriomaintx_port_lt_ctl_s  cn63xxp1;
05475     struct cvmx_sriomaintx_port_lt_ctl_s  cn66xx;
05476     struct cvmx_sriomaintx_port_lt_ctl_s  cnf75xx;
05477 };

05509 /**
05510  * cvmx_sriomaint#_port_rt_ctl
05511  *
05512  * This register controls the timeout for logical layer transactions. It is used under
05513  * two conditions. First, it is used as the timeout period between sending a packet
05514  * requiring a packet response being sent to receiving the corresponding response. This
05515  * is used for all outgoing packet types including memory, maintenance, doorbells and
05516  * message operations. When the timeout period expires the packet is disgarded and the
05517  * error is logged in the PKT_TOUT field of the SRIOMAINT()_ERB_LT_ERR_DET
05518  * register. The second use of this register is as a timeout period between incoming
05519  * message segments of the same message. If a message segment is received then the
05520  * MSG_TOUT field of the SRIOMAINT()_ERB_LT_ERR_DET register is set if the next segment
05521  * has not been received before the time expires. In both cases, each count represents
05522  * 200 ns. The minimum timeout period is the TIMEOUT x 200 ns and the maximum is twice
05523  * that number. A value less than 32 may not guarantee that all timeout errors will be
05524  * reported correctly. A value of 0 disables the logical layer timeouts and is not
05525  * recommended for normal operation.
05526  */
05527 union cvmx_sriomaintx_port_rt_ctl {
05528     uint32_t u32;
05529     struct cvmx_sriomaintx_port_rt_ctl_s {
05530 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
05531     uint32_t timeout                      : 24; /**< Timeout value. */
05532     uint32_t reserved_0_7                 : 8;
05533 #else
05534     uint32_t reserved_0_7                 : 8;
05535     uint32_t timeout                      : 24;
05536 #endif
05537     } s;
05538     struct cvmx_sriomaintx_port_rt_ctl_s  cn63xx;
05539     struct cvmx_sriomaintx_port_rt_ctl_s  cn63xxp1;
05540     struct cvmx_sriomaintx_port_rt_ctl_s  cn66xx;
05541     struct cvmx_sriomaintx_port_rt_ctl_s  cnf75xx;
05542 };
05543 typedef union cvmx_sriomaintx_port_rt_ctl cvmx_sriomaintx_port_rt_ctl_t;
05544 
05545 /**
05546  * cvmx_sriomaint#_port_ttl_ctl
05547  *
05548  * This register controls the timeout for outgoing packets. It is primilarly
05549  * used to make sure packets are being transmitted and acknowledged within a
05550  * reasonable period of time. The timeout value corresponds to TIMEOUT x 200 ns
05551  * and a value of 0 disables the timer. The actual value should be greater
05552  * than the physical layer timeout specified in SRIOMAINT()_PORT_LT_CTL and
05553  * is typically a less than the response timeout specified in
05554  * SRIOMAINT()_PORT_RT_CTL.
05555  * A second application of this timer is to remove all the packets waiting
05556  * to be transmitted including those already in flight. This may by necessary
05557  * for the case of a link going down (see SRIO()_INT_REG[LINK_DWN]).  Packet
05558  * removal can accomplished by setting the TIMEOUT value to small number so
05559  * that all TX packets can be dropped.
05560  *
05561  * In both cases, when the timeout expires the TTL interrupt is asserted, any
05562  * packets currently being transmitted are dropped, the SRIOMAINT()_TX_DROP[DROP]
05563  * bit is set (causing any scheduled packets to be dropped), the
05564  * SRIOMAINT()_TX_DROP[DROP_CNT] is incremented for each packet and the SRIO
05565  * output state is set to IDLE (all errors are cleared). Software must clear
05566  * the SRIOMAINT()_TX_DROP[DROP] bit to resume transmitting packets.
05567  */
05568 union cvmx_sriomaintx_port_ttl_ctl {
05569     uint32_t u32;
05570     struct cvmx_sriomaintx_port_ttl_ctl_s {
05571 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
05572     uint32_t timeout                      : 24; /**< Timeout value. */
05573     uint32_t reserved_0_7                 : 8;
05574 #else
05575     uint32_t reserved_0_7                 : 8;
05576     uint32_t timeout                      : 24;
05577 #endif
05578     } s;
05579     struct cvmx_sriomaintx_port_ttl_ctl_s cn63xx;
05580     struct cvmx_sriomaintx_port_ttl_ctl_s cn66xx;
05581     struct cvmx_sriomaintx_port_ttl_ctl_s cnf75xx;
05582 };
05583 typedef union cvmx_sriomaintx_port_ttl_ctl cvmx_sriomaintx_port_ttl_ctl_t;
05584

05792 /**
05793  * cvmx_sriomaint#_tx_drop
05794  *
05795  * This register controls and provides status for dropping outgoing SRIO packets.  The DROP bit
05796  * should only be cleared when no packets are currently being dropped.  This can be guaranteed by
05797  * clearing SRIOMAINT()_PORT_0_CTL[O_ENABLE] before changing the DROP bit and
05798  * restoring the O_ENABLE afterwards.
05799  */
05800 union cvmx_sriomaintx_tx_drop {
05801     uint32_t u32;
05802     struct cvmx_sriomaintx_tx_drop_s {
05803 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
05804     uint32_t reserved_17_31               : 15;
05805     uint32_t drop                         : 1;  /**< All outgoing packets are dropped.  Any packets
05806                                                          requiring a response will return 1's after the
05807                                                          SRIOMAINT()_PORT_RT_CTL timeout expires.  This bit
05808                                                          is set automatically when the TTL Timeout occurs
05809                                                          or can be set by software and must always be
05810                                                          cleared by software. */
05811     uint32_t drop_cnt                     : 16; /**< Number of packets dropped by transmit logic.
05812                                                          Packets are dropped whenever a packet is ready to
05813                                                          be transmitted and a TTL Timeouts occur, the  DROP
05814                                                          bit is set or the SRIOMAINT()_ERB_ERR_RATE_THR
05815                                                          FAIL_TH has been reached and the DROP_PKT bit is
05816                                                          set in SRIOMAINT()_PORT_0_CTL.  This counter wraps
05817                                                          on overflow and is cleared only on reset. */
05818 #else
05819     uint32_t drop_cnt                     : 16;
05820     uint32_t drop                         : 1;
05821     uint32_t reserved_17_31               : 15;
05822 #endif
05823     } s;
05824     struct cvmx_sriomaintx_tx_drop_s      cn63xx;
05825     struct cvmx_sriomaintx_tx_drop_s      cn66xx;
05826     struct cvmx_sriomaintx_tx_drop_s      cnf75xx;
05827 };
05828 typedef union cvmx_sriomaintx_tx_drop cvmx_sriomaintx_tx_drop_t;
